Sure. Here's a possible data model for a test automation tool considering organizations, users, projects, goals (under projects), tests (under goals) and executions (of test cases). Each execution has a date and a passed or failed status.

**Entity Relationship Diagram:**
```
    Organization        
                 |
                 V
                User
                 |
                 V
              Project --> Goal --> Test --> Execution
```

**Database Schema:**
```
CREATE TABLE organization (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE user (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    username TEXT NOT NULL,
    password TEXT NOT NULL,
    organization_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT user_ibfk_1 FOREIGN KEY (organization_id) REFERENCES organization(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);

CREATE TABLE project (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    organization_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT project_ibfk_1 FOREIGN KEY (organization_id) REFERENCES organization(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);

CREATE TABLE goal (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    project_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT goal_ibfk_1 FOREIGN KEY (project_id) REFERENCES project(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);

CREATE TABLE test (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    name TEXT NOT NULL,
    goal_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT test_ibfk_1 FOREIGN KEY (goal_id) REFERENCES goal(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);

CREATE TABLE execution (
    id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
    test_id INTEGER NOT NULL,
    date TIMESTAMP NOT NULL,
    passed BOOLEAN NOT NULL,
    CONSTRAINT execution_ibfk_1 FOREIGN KEY (test_id) REFERENCES test(id) ON DELETE CASCADE
);
```

